00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:54.940
Yeah.

00:19:54.940 --> 00:19:58.090
So I wanted to talk to you
a bit about the inspiration

00:19:58.090 --> 00:20:00.950
for your album, which has one
of the coolest album titles,

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:01.450
I think--

00:20:01.450 --> 00:20:03.370
"Upside Down Flowers."

00:20:03.370 --> 00:20:05.350
So I was reading on your site.

00:20:05.350 --> 00:20:07.790
You said that you called it
that because, in many ways,

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:09.400
it's a mirror to my world--

00:20:09.400 --> 00:20:12.460
an uncanny reflection, but
not quite the real thing.

00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:15.190
Could you talk a little bit
more about that uncanny nature

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:16.330
of reality?

00:20:16.330 --> 00:20:17.205
ANDREW MCMAHON: Yeah.

00:20:17.205 --> 00:20:19.690
You know, what's interesting
about the genesis

00:20:19.690 --> 00:20:23.247
of this record was that a lot
of times you start records

00:20:23.247 --> 00:20:24.830
and you know you're
starting a record,

00:20:24.830 --> 00:20:27.310
or you know you're
in the process.

00:20:27.310 --> 00:20:30.700
And instead, with this
album, I had this rare moment

00:20:30.700 --> 00:20:36.790
where, after two full records
of touring and creating,

00:20:36.790 --> 00:20:38.440
I had a few months off at home.

00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:41.800
Which is something that,
since I started this project,

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:43.220
I had not had in a while.

00:20:43.220 --> 00:20:45.910
And the process began with--

00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:47.945
I watched this
documentary, "Abstract."

00:20:47.945 --> 00:20:50.320
Which I don't know if you guys
have seen this on Netflix,

00:20:50.320 --> 00:20:53.290
but it's a documentary
about just creatives

00:20:53.290 --> 00:20:55.750
and the different
threads of success

00:20:55.750 --> 00:20:57.160
through their creative lives.

00:20:57.160 --> 00:20:59.320
And the one thing
that struck me--

00:20:59.320 --> 00:21:01.060
and I've always
known to be true,

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:03.760
but it's easy sometimes to
forget when you are an artist

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:06.700
who tours like we do--

00:21:06.700 --> 00:21:09.480
that you've got to put
yourself in the position

00:21:09.480 --> 00:21:11.040
to create every day.

00:21:11.040 --> 00:21:13.885
And when I got home and
I had this block of time,

00:21:13.885 --> 00:21:16.510
I think usually what I might do
is take a couple weeks and just

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:18.820
sort of flounder and
hang out with the family

00:21:18.820 --> 00:21:20.050
and see old friends.

00:21:20.050 --> 00:21:21.220
And I did all that.

00:21:21.220 --> 00:21:22.960
But my daughter was
finally school age.

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:27.280
So I started working in
the back house studio where

00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:30.430
I wrote this record and
just created my own writing

00:21:30.430 --> 00:21:33.100
practice based around the day.

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:36.400
And what ended up creeping
up were a combination

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:37.570
of these memories--

00:21:37.570 --> 00:21:40.467
like the one you heard in
"Ohio," which is very much,

00:21:40.467 --> 00:21:42.550
in a way, a kind of a vivid
portrayal of something

00:21:42.550 --> 00:21:45.910
that happened to me when I was
a kid to a song like "Paper

00:21:45.910 --> 00:21:49.270
Rain," which was, I
think, true in some senses

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:52.090
philosophically, about
this idea of living life

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:53.200
as a bit of a gamble.

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:55.990
But it was very much
a story that kind of

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:58.300
came to me in the middle
of that writing process

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:01.240
and became the story
of somebody else.

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:03.570
But somehow, a piece
of me existed in there,

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:04.690
if that makes sense.

00:22:04.690 --> 00:22:06.270
SPEAKER: Yeah, definitely.

00:22:06.270 --> 00:22:10.480
I found "Ohio" very moving,
both figuratively and literally,

00:22:10.480 --> 00:22:14.030
as it talks about your move
from Ohio to California.

00:22:14.030 --> 00:22:17.620
And I know you referred to it
as sort of a pilgrimage for you.

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:19.540
So what did that mean
for you as a child,

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:22.540
moving from the Midwest out
to the land where it's always

00:22:22.540 --> 00:22:24.365
sunny and warm and all that?

00:22:24.365 --> 00:22:25.240
ANDREW MCMAHON: Yeah.

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:27.700
I mean, admittedly
my family-- we were

00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:31.030
all in a bit of a tricky time.

00:22:31.030 --> 00:22:33.280
Around then, I was about
11 or 12 years old.

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:36.010
And we had sort of gone
on the roller coaster

00:22:36.010 --> 00:22:38.410
of having done
very well, and then

00:22:38.410 --> 00:22:41.280
had kind of lost
everything to some extent.

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:43.090
And we had family
on the West Coast.

00:22:43.090 --> 00:22:44.530
It was, like, those were
the cousins we always went

00:22:44.530 --> 00:22:45.640
to visit in the summertime.

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:45.880
You know?

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:47.290
And that was a great summer.

00:22:47.290 --> 00:22:48.670
Every summer, you're like, oh!

00:22:48.670 --> 00:22:50.100
I grew up kind of
Midwest, East Coast,

00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:52.100
where we could go to
California for the summers.

00:22:52.100 --> 00:22:54.850
And in a sense, it always felt
like the promised land to me,

00:22:54.850 --> 00:22:55.730
you know?

00:22:55.730 --> 00:22:59.150
And when we found
ourselves with so little,

00:22:59.150 --> 00:23:01.150
it just made sense to go
be with my mom's family

00:23:01.150 --> 00:23:01.930
on the West Coast.

00:23:01.930 --> 00:23:06.010
And I think, for me, as
hard as that time was,

00:23:06.010 --> 00:23:07.570
and for my family,
as hard as it was,

00:23:07.570 --> 00:23:09.460
it was where we sort
of rebuilt our lives

00:23:09.460 --> 00:23:11.050
and built a new
story for ourselves.

00:23:11.050 --> 00:23:14.290
And for me, it was
the place where

00:23:14.290 --> 00:23:16.830
I was able to really
explore my songwriting.

00:23:16.830 --> 00:23:18.830
I had written for years
prior to our move there.

00:23:18.830 --> 00:23:21.520
But this was the place
where I built my first band.

00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:23.480
I found those kind
of close friends

00:23:23.480 --> 00:23:25.480
that, when you're somebody
who moves every three

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:28.360
years as a kid, you don't get
to make those close connections.

00:23:28.360 --> 00:23:32.570
And I think it did feel, and
it still does to this day,

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:34.780
it's not my native home.

00:23:34.780 --> 00:23:37.680
But it's about as native
feeling as I know--

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:40.820
is the beach towns of
Southern California.

00:23:40.820 --> 00:23:43.090
SPEAKER: So like a lot
of people, probably,

00:23:43.090 --> 00:23:45.070
in the audience, my
favorite song of yours

00:23:45.070 --> 00:23:47.377
is "Cecilia and The Satellite",
which you just played.

00:23:47.377 --> 00:23:49.460
And you give a little bit
of the background in it.

00:23:49.460 --> 00:23:51.713
But it's such a
beautiful love song.

00:23:51.713 --> 00:23:53.380
But what's, I think,
so special about it

00:23:53.380 --> 00:23:55.480
is we don't hear a whole
lot of rock love songs

00:23:55.480 --> 00:23:56.960
from parents to children.

00:23:56.960 --> 00:24:01.910
It's usually a different kind
of romantic type of song.

00:24:01.910 --> 00:24:04.090
So I was wondering if you'd
talk a little bit more

00:24:04.090 --> 00:24:06.280
about the genesis
and also how does

00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:07.478
your daughter feel about it?

00:24:07.478 --> 00:24:09.520
Do you play it for her a
lot, that sort of thing?

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:11.937
ANDREW MCMAHON: Any song that
references her-- my daughter

00:24:11.937 --> 00:24:12.738
is a huge fan of.

00:24:12.738 --> 00:24:15.280
I'm sure that is going to change
within the next four or five

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:15.780
years.

00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:18.670
But as of now, I mean, even
on, like, even on "Paper Rain",

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:19.540
there's that lyric,
you know? (SINGING)

00:24:19.540 --> 00:24:21.910
I've got mouths to feed, I'm
going to get-- (SPEAKING)

00:24:21.910 --> 00:24:24.310
--but my daughter goes, that's
my mouth you have to feed.

00:24:24.310 --> 00:24:25.685
You're, like,
thank you, Cecilia.

00:24:25.685 --> 00:24:26.570
Yeah, she knows.

00:24:26.570 --> 00:24:32.770
She's keenly aware of where
she fits into my catalog now.

00:24:32.770 --> 00:24:33.940
Yeah.

00:24:33.940 --> 00:24:37.780
For me, and I'm sure we can
touch on this at some point,

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:42.430
you know, "Cecilia" is a
product of a very tricky time

00:24:42.430 --> 00:24:43.440
in my life.

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:44.500
I'm a cancer survivor.

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:47.623
And you know, I was sort
of rendered infertile

00:24:47.623 --> 00:24:48.790
as a part of that treatment.

00:24:48.790 --> 00:24:51.780
I apologize to get a little
gross here for you all.

00:24:51.780 --> 00:24:53.620
But there's this
kind of joking story

00:24:53.620 --> 00:24:55.150
that I've told, if you've
been to one of my shows.

00:24:55.150 --> 00:24:55.930
It's not really a joke.

00:24:55.930 --> 00:24:56.430
It's true.

00:24:56.430 --> 00:25:00.430
That in the process of
being a sick person,

00:25:00.430 --> 00:25:03.910
finding out that you're going
to be infertile, at least,

00:25:03.910 --> 00:25:06.592
for me--

00:25:06.592 --> 00:25:08.050
I was lucky to have
a doctor to say

00:25:08.050 --> 00:25:09.310
you've got to bank your sperm.

00:25:09.310 --> 00:25:11.470
And that's going to-- maybe
one day you'll have a family.

00:25:11.470 --> 00:25:12.790
And I was, like, I don't care.

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:13.990
I was 22 at the time.

00:25:13.990 --> 00:25:17.420
I was just-- that's not really
of interest to me right now.

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:19.810
Let's load me up with
the chemo, whatever,

00:25:19.810 --> 00:25:21.190
and let's kill this cancer.

00:25:21.190 --> 00:25:24.915
And eventually, what ended up
happening was he was, like,

00:25:24.915 --> 00:25:26.540
I won't treat you if
you don't do this.

00:25:26.540 --> 00:25:28.300
So I did.

00:25:28.300 --> 00:25:30.760
And you know,
miraculously, years pass.

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:32.597
And my wife and I
got to this place

00:25:32.597 --> 00:25:34.180
where, like, we do
want to have a kid.

00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:37.120
And we went through
this IVF process.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:40.190
And I met this little person.

00:25:40.190 --> 00:25:46.340
And I think, in a weird way,
telling that story and meeting

00:25:46.340 --> 00:25:48.590
my daughter was the thing
that kind of closed the loop

00:25:48.590 --> 00:25:49.970
on my cancer experience.

00:25:49.970 --> 00:25:52.890
Because I met the most
important person in my life,

00:25:52.890 --> 00:25:56.550
or one of them, because
of that experience.

00:25:56.550 --> 00:25:58.790
And so I think when I
was writing that song,

00:25:58.790 --> 00:26:00.060
I felt all of those things.

00:26:00.060 --> 00:26:04.040
That's why, instead of it
becoming just an ordinary love

00:26:04.040 --> 00:26:07.070
song, it really became
me trying to educate

00:26:07.070 --> 00:26:10.020
my daughter on the person I had
been, the things that I'd seen,

00:26:10.020 --> 00:26:14.060
and let her know that those
peaks and valleys in life

00:26:14.060 --> 00:26:16.988
are going to come to us all.

00:26:16.988 --> 00:26:18.530
But also that my
hope is that I could

00:26:18.530 --> 00:26:21.890
be there to walk that
road with her as much

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:24.520
as humanly possible.

00:26:24.520 --> 00:26:27.560
And I love that it
became my biggest song.

00:26:27.560 --> 00:26:31.430
Because there are oftentimes
people in this business

00:26:31.430 --> 00:26:35.420
that will try and force you into
the lowest common denominator

00:26:35.420 --> 00:26:37.460
to reach the most
amount of people.

00:26:37.460 --> 00:26:40.430
And what I found is
historically what's

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:42.590
been successful for
me has been the most

00:26:42.590 --> 00:26:46.040
specificity and the most
sort of leaning into my story

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:47.910
and trying to find
those tangible threads.

00:26:47.910 --> 00:26:50.870
Those universal threads have
been what have kind of led me

00:26:50.870 --> 00:26:52.360
to the largest audience.

00:26:52.360 --> 00:26:54.620
SPEAKER: Yeah, I think there's
a lot of truth to that.

00:26:54.620 --> 00:26:56.720
That when you get
more specific, it

00:26:56.720 --> 00:27:00.330
becomes universal at the
same time sometimes, too.

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:03.410
So I can't imagine what
that was like, getting

00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:05.420
a cancer diagnosis that young.

00:27:05.420 --> 00:27:08.780
And I'm sure that
that greatly impacted

00:27:08.780 --> 00:27:11.030
not just your life, but the
trajectory of your career.

00:27:11.030 --> 00:27:13.520
Just in terms of going
through that experience,

00:27:13.520 --> 00:27:18.200
being a survivor, do you feel
like that has affected like all

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:19.455
of the music you wrote since?

00:27:19.455 --> 00:27:20.330
ANDREW MCMAHON: Yeah.

00:27:20.330 --> 00:27:23.990
I mean, I think the dangerous
game of survivorship

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:28.120
is trying to look at your
life as these sliding doors,

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:28.620
you know?

00:27:28.620 --> 00:27:30.620
And saying, well, gosh,
if that hadn't happened,

00:27:30.620 --> 00:27:31.830
where would I be now?

00:27:31.830 --> 00:27:34.220
And I think it's
taken me years to sort

00:27:34.220 --> 00:27:36.500
of unlearn that mentality.

00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:37.880
And say, well, this did happen.

00:27:37.880 --> 00:27:42.210
You know, this is the
way that your life went.

00:27:42.210 --> 00:27:42.710
You know?

00:27:42.710 --> 00:27:46.670
But it took me a lot
of years to figure out,

00:27:46.670 --> 00:27:49.760
just as you build good
memories on the other side

00:27:49.760 --> 00:27:53.100
of some trauma, that
becomes your life.

00:27:53.100 --> 00:27:55.880
And that can be a really
beautiful existence.

00:27:55.880 --> 00:27:59.610
But certainly it worked its
way into my creative process.

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:01.460
It worked its way, and
it was hard to create

00:28:01.460 --> 00:28:02.340
after being sick.

00:28:02.340 --> 00:28:03.945
I went from being
this fearless--

00:28:03.945 --> 00:28:06.320
you know, I made these records,
and I'd gotten successful

00:28:06.320 --> 00:28:08.900
at such a young age, that
all of a sudden now I

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:13.490
had this ghost in every room
with me, going, you know?

00:28:13.490 --> 00:28:15.425
Every decision became
much trickier to make.

00:28:15.425 --> 00:28:17.300
It was, like, everything
became life or death

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:23.600
after seeing life and death
in that frame at a young age.

00:28:23.600 --> 00:28:25.540
But it's taught me a lot.

00:28:25.540 --> 00:28:27.680
And at this point,
I wouldn't trade it.

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:30.470
So much, like I said, has
happened because of it.

00:28:30.470 --> 00:28:33.350
And I've been able to
make a lot of change

00:28:33.350 --> 00:28:35.360
and try and raise a
lot of money for people

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:37.580
who've been in my position.

00:28:37.580 --> 00:28:39.530
And that's been really
rewarding work for me.

00:28:39.530 --> 00:28:42.170
SPEAKER: You're definitely an
inspiration to a lot of people,

00:28:42.170 --> 00:28:44.180
having gone through
that and continuing

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:45.560
to create afterwards.

00:28:45.560 --> 00:28:48.260
So on a lighter note,
I learned that you're

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:49.850
an amateur mixologist.

00:28:49.850 --> 00:28:51.920
You just kicked off
a new video series

00:28:51.920 --> 00:28:53.970
on YouTube, "The Rocktail Hour."

00:28:53.970 --> 00:28:55.970
Could you talk a bit
about that, your interest

00:28:55.970 --> 00:28:58.515
in cocktails and your hobbies?

00:28:58.515 --> 00:28:59.390
ANDREW MCMAHON: Yeah.

00:28:59.390 --> 00:29:02.540
I mean, I got a buzz
on at home one night.

00:29:02.540 --> 00:29:04.860
And these phones,
as we all know,

00:29:04.860 --> 00:29:06.920
sometimes you'll
maybe shoot a video

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:10.010
that you shouldn't shoot when
you've had too much to drink.

00:29:10.010 --> 00:29:12.290
And I think it was a margarita.

00:29:12.290 --> 00:29:13.850
I have a house margarita I make.

00:29:13.850 --> 00:29:16.040
Then I was just, like, all
right, kids, here we go.

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:16.540
You know?

00:29:16.540 --> 00:29:21.800
And it just turned into
this thing for my fans.

00:29:21.800 --> 00:29:25.530
They loved that window
into to my world.

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:28.670
And I think that that's a lesson
learned for me as somebody

00:29:28.670 --> 00:29:31.460
who is not a early
adopter of technology,

00:29:31.460 --> 00:29:35.120
but somebody who very much
has to be thrust and forced.

00:29:35.120 --> 00:29:38.920
Like, my manager's going, you
need to post on Instagram.

00:29:38.920 --> 00:29:39.500
And now I do.

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:40.417
And I love that stuff.

00:29:40.417 --> 00:29:42.560
But yes, we started this series.

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:44.930
A buddy of mine has a
bar in town where I live.

00:29:44.930 --> 00:29:47.330
And he wrote all those recipes
and was behind the camera

00:29:47.330 --> 00:29:48.440
going, now you do this.

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:50.210
Now you do that.

00:29:50.210 --> 00:29:54.050
I make, like, three drinks well
and then quickly forget them.

00:29:54.050 --> 00:29:55.160
But yeah.

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:55.790
It's fun.

00:29:55.790 --> 00:29:59.180
It's a nice meditation at
the end of the night for me

00:29:59.180 --> 00:30:02.407
to just make a single
drink for myself and enjoy.

00:30:02.407 --> 00:30:04.490
SPEAKER: We have some time
