00:30:35.630 --> 00:30:38.000
has changed a lot
over those years.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:41.390
Who you are has changed
a lot over those years.

00:30:41.390 --> 00:30:44.390
As a musician, though,
the music that you've made

00:30:44.390 --> 00:30:45.350
is permanent, right?

00:30:45.350 --> 00:30:46.430
It's on record.

00:30:46.430 --> 00:30:49.550
And there's some expectation
that you perform that old music

00:30:49.550 --> 00:30:50.840
from time to time.

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:54.710
What is that like for you
being a very different person

00:30:54.710 --> 00:30:57.625
than that person that
wrote those old songs?

00:30:57.625 --> 00:30:58.500
ANDREW MCMAHON: Yeah.

00:30:58.500 --> 00:31:00.530
You know, it's interesting.

00:31:00.530 --> 00:31:03.770
I look at all of the
chapters of my first band,

00:31:03.770 --> 00:31:06.160
Something Corporate, Jack's
Mannequin, this record.

00:31:06.160 --> 00:31:09.560
I don't necessarily look at
them as different people-- maybe

00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:12.140
different lives, to some
extent, or different chapters

00:31:12.140 --> 00:31:14.210
of a life.

00:31:14.210 --> 00:31:17.330
And sure there are some
songs from my back catalog

00:31:17.330 --> 00:31:19.540
that maybe I don't favor.

00:31:19.540 --> 00:31:22.370
I would rather not play.

00:31:22.370 --> 00:31:25.190
But what's interesting is I find
that the ones that are enduring

00:31:25.190 --> 00:31:26.780
and the ones that people
talk about the most,

00:31:26.780 --> 00:31:28.697
those are the ones that
matter to me the most.

00:31:28.697 --> 00:31:31.850
Kind of speaking to this idea
of when you write something that

00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:33.680
feels very true
to yourself, even

00:31:33.680 --> 00:31:37.010
if it's in some sort
of fledgling state

00:31:37.010 --> 00:31:42.623
or some moment of growth, those
things still feel relevant.

00:31:42.623 --> 00:31:44.540
You know, when I play
those songs, and we do--

00:31:44.540 --> 00:31:46.700
we do quite a bit of
back catalog in my set,

00:31:46.700 --> 00:31:50.030
it's always kind of a
combination of the newest

00:31:50.030 --> 00:31:51.000
record--

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.510
certainly I try and
lean heavy on whatever

00:31:53.510 --> 00:31:54.960
project I'm working
specifically,

00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:56.960
so there's a lot of
Wilderness songs in the set.

00:31:56.960 --> 00:31:59.030
But the other half
of the set is kind

00:31:59.030 --> 00:32:03.260
of a mash up of the bigger
songs from Jack's and Something

00:32:03.260 --> 00:32:03.830
Corporate.

00:32:03.830 --> 00:32:08.270
And then sort of the ones on the
outskirts that I like the most,

00:32:08.270 --> 00:32:11.270
or that fans talk
about the most.

00:32:11.270 --> 00:32:13.700
And playing them live--

00:32:13.700 --> 00:32:15.280
it still feels good.

00:32:15.280 --> 00:32:17.885
If it doesn't, then I generally
kind of jettison those.

00:32:17.885 --> 00:32:19.260
Or I try and find
different ways.

00:32:19.260 --> 00:32:21.440
There's a song called
"Punk Rock Princess"

00:32:21.440 --> 00:32:23.300
from when I was in high school.

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:24.920
You know?

00:32:24.920 --> 00:32:27.720
And we're doing it with a
full band for the first time

00:32:27.720 --> 00:32:28.220
in forever.

00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:30.380
Because this record
and this tour

00:32:30.380 --> 00:32:34.040
is sort of a bit of a nostalgia
bent, because the album

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:36.680
itself is so reflective.

00:32:36.680 --> 00:32:38.900
But with that song, I've
been doing that as a ballad

00:32:38.900 --> 00:32:40.620
on and off for the
last few years.

00:32:40.620 --> 00:32:45.140
And as a ballad, I feel like
the earnestness of being young

00:32:45.140 --> 00:32:48.490
and what it is to sort
of pursue somebody

00:32:48.490 --> 00:32:51.240
who doesn't like the
same music that you like,

00:32:51.240 --> 00:32:52.670
which I think is a--

00:32:52.670 --> 00:32:56.677
you know, I can still
identify with that somehow.

00:32:56.677 --> 00:32:57.510
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:32:57.510 --> 00:32:58.590
ANDREW MCMAHON: Thank you.

00:32:58.590 --> 00:33:00.120
AUDIENCE: That guy sort
of stole my question.

00:33:00.120 --> 00:33:01.745
But it's more about
just your evolution

00:33:01.745 --> 00:33:03.240
of music over the years.

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:08.170
I mean, I feel like there's
pieces that seem very Something

00:33:08.170 --> 00:33:08.670
Corporate-y.

00:33:08.670 --> 00:33:10.378
But then, obviously,
you've changed a lot

00:33:10.378 --> 00:33:12.830
through life
experiences, et cetera.

00:33:12.830 --> 00:33:15.260
I'm just curious
how what you learned

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:17.000
and what you experienced
in the Something

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:18.950
Corporate days, how
that impacted you

00:33:18.950 --> 00:33:22.190
when it went to Jack's Mannequin
and now your solo career,

00:33:22.190 --> 00:33:25.850
what pieces you took with
you, what you maybe discarded.

00:33:25.850 --> 00:33:27.480
Do you miss that period of time?

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:28.910
And then what's next?

00:33:28.910 --> 00:33:31.575
What's next on your kind of
trajectory here with music?

00:33:31.575 --> 00:33:32.450
ANDREW MCMAHON: Yeah.

00:33:32.450 --> 00:33:36.200
I mean, well, to the first
part, I think, like any of us,

00:33:36.200 --> 00:33:38.810
we're trying to evolve.

00:33:38.810 --> 00:33:43.970
And I think that's
been my biggest target.

00:33:43.970 --> 00:33:45.770
Just don't settle
and don't stay.

00:33:45.770 --> 00:33:48.020
And that's why I've continued
to change project names.

00:33:48.020 --> 00:33:50.840
And people kind of hate
me for it on some level.

00:33:50.840 --> 00:33:52.370
Because they're,
like, oh, new band?

00:33:52.370 --> 00:33:53.030
OK.

00:33:53.030 --> 00:33:55.303
But historically,
most of the time,

00:33:55.303 --> 00:33:57.720
I have a lot of the same players
or producers or whatever.

00:33:57.720 --> 00:33:59.095
We're all involved
in this thing.

00:33:59.095 --> 00:34:02.030
And it's just more about
delineating time for me.

00:34:02.030 --> 00:34:04.910
The thing that I take from
the Something Corporate era

00:34:04.910 --> 00:34:08.889
for me is just I think
about collaboration.

00:34:08.889 --> 00:34:11.190
I wasn't a great
collaborator in those days.

00:34:11.190 --> 00:34:14.764
I think I was a very guarded
collaborator when I started.

00:34:14.764 --> 00:34:16.520
You know, you're a
kid in high school.

00:34:16.520 --> 00:34:18.556
And you and your best
friends, you know,

00:34:18.556 --> 00:34:19.889
you're making a record together.

00:34:19.889 --> 00:34:23.350
And all of a sudden
then it blows up.

00:34:23.350 --> 00:34:26.239
And then it gets political,
or whatever it is.

00:34:26.239 --> 00:34:28.400
And I'm still close
with all those guys,

00:34:28.400 --> 00:34:30.770
because I think we did
what a lot of bands

00:34:30.770 --> 00:34:32.520
and a lot of our
contemporaries didn't do,

00:34:32.520 --> 00:34:35.100
which-- they stayed in it long
enough to hate each other,

00:34:35.100 --> 00:34:35.600
you know?

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:38.437
Where it's, like, we did
the most mature thing

00:34:38.437 --> 00:34:39.020
we could have.

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:40.570
Which was, like,
we're best friends,

00:34:40.570 --> 00:34:44.892
we're not getting along so
well, let's take a break.

00:34:44.892 --> 00:34:46.850
And I think what I've
tried to learn over time,

00:34:46.850 --> 00:34:49.159
and I think really
in a large way what

00:34:49.159 --> 00:34:51.560
the Wilderness is
a reflection of,

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:54.080
is how in those first two
projects, Something Corporate

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:59.480
and Jack's, I could carry a
chip on my shoulder, which

00:34:59.480 --> 00:35:03.510
is just not a healthy way to try
and create or build anything.

00:35:03.510 --> 00:35:04.010
You know?

00:35:04.010 --> 00:35:05.930
If something didn't
go right or the launch

00:35:05.930 --> 00:35:08.360
of an album or a
single didn't take,

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:12.750
I would be pointing fingers.

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:15.020
And with collaboration,
again, I was a little bit more

00:35:15.020 --> 00:35:16.560
of a jealous collaborator.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:17.560
I was always guarded.

00:35:17.560 --> 00:35:22.910
And with this project, it really
became about opening myself up.

00:35:22.910 --> 00:35:24.920
Not being afraid
to get in a room

00:35:24.920 --> 00:35:27.900
and write with somebody
who I admired or respected,

00:35:27.900 --> 00:35:30.290
not being afraid to
travel here or there,

00:35:30.290 --> 00:35:34.430
or meet this producer, or listen
to what a trusted manager had

00:35:34.430 --> 00:35:35.540
to say about a song.

00:35:35.540 --> 00:35:38.540
Because they want
me to win, you know?

00:35:38.540 --> 00:35:42.000
And I think those are
the big lessons of now.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:44.450
And I think a lot of that is
just age and getting older.

00:35:44.450 --> 00:35:49.910
And saying do you want to walk
through life with your fists

00:35:49.910 --> 00:35:52.790
up all the time, or do you
want to sort of move through it

00:35:52.790 --> 00:35:55.088
in a peaceful way?

00:35:55.088 --> 00:35:56.630
And I'd say those
are the big lessons

00:35:56.630 --> 00:35:58.190
I learned from the early days.

00:35:58.190 --> 00:36:02.090
As far as what's next,
I'm not 100% sure.

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:06.260
I'm in that bizarre
flux moment now where

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:10.640
this tour feels like it's doing
an amazing job of rounding out

00:36:10.640 --> 00:36:11.268
this project.

00:36:11.268 --> 00:36:13.310
I don't think I'm walking
away from this project.

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:14.840
But there's some
talk about maybe

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:17.510
doing some scoring work and
some film and television

00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:18.450
stuff when I get home.

00:36:18.450 --> 00:36:23.270
And I'm working on some other
projects for people who are not

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:25.810
just myself, but
actually contributing

00:36:25.810 --> 00:36:28.740
to some other
avenues creatively.

00:36:28.740 --> 00:36:30.140
So time will tell.

00:36:30.140 --> 00:36:31.900
But I'll always be making songs.

