married now for 10 years,

00:36:56.270 --> 00:36:58.140
and we've got three kids.

00:36:58.140 --> 00:37:01.137
My seven-year-old daughter-- her
favorite song is "Fire Escape."

00:37:01.137 --> 00:37:01.970
ANDREW MCMAHON: Mhm.

00:37:01.970 --> 00:37:05.160
AUDIENCE: And we sing it
to her almost every night.

00:37:05.160 --> 00:37:09.860
But the question I want to ask
is, my son is 11 years old.

00:37:09.860 --> 00:37:12.830
And he's getting
into music a lot.

00:37:12.830 --> 00:37:15.420
He's taking piano
lessons and guitar.

00:37:15.420 --> 00:37:19.250
What advice would you give
to the parent of someone who

00:37:19.250 --> 00:37:20.750
really wants to get into music?

00:37:20.750 --> 00:37:23.292
ANDREW MCMAHON: The best advice
that I can give at this point

00:37:23.292 --> 00:37:24.740
is to do what my parents did.

00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:30.140
Which, you know, my
parents just supported me.

00:37:30.140 --> 00:37:33.080
They never really
drove the whole--

00:37:33.080 --> 00:37:34.310
you have to go to lessons.

00:37:34.310 --> 00:37:37.160
I eventually asked for
lessons, because I was writing.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:39.450
And I started by writing.

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:41.860
I learned a couple chords
and that was the beginning

00:37:41.860 --> 00:37:42.860
of my writing adventure.

00:37:42.860 --> 00:37:44.360
And then after about
a year of that,

00:37:44.360 --> 00:37:47.100
I couldn't make any new sounds
or shapes with my fingers.

00:37:47.100 --> 00:37:48.650
And so I asked for lessons.

00:37:48.650 --> 00:37:51.230
I mean, they were diligent
about trying to make sure I went

00:37:51.230 --> 00:37:52.940
and that I didn't
waste their money.

00:37:55.690 --> 00:37:57.520
But I think about my mom.

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:00.740
Like, when I started
writing songs,

00:38:00.740 --> 00:38:02.365
all the other kids
were playing sports.

00:38:02.365 --> 00:38:03.282
You know, what I mean?

00:38:03.282 --> 00:38:05.330
And my oldest-- I'm the
youngest of five-- all

00:38:05.330 --> 00:38:07.538
of my older brothers and
sisters were great athletes.

00:38:07.538 --> 00:38:09.350
I was not a good athlete.

00:38:09.350 --> 00:38:12.830
And instead, my parents
saw that I had a passion,

00:38:12.830 --> 00:38:14.150
and they backed it.

00:38:14.150 --> 00:38:17.000
And you know, my mom
looked up music producer

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.900
in the yellow pages
when I was 10 years old

00:38:19.900 --> 00:38:22.760
and drove me to Dayton, Ohio.

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:27.080
And I worked in this guy's
little home studio, which

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:29.270
was a fairly new
thing at that point,

00:38:29.270 --> 00:38:31.610
and made a three song demo tape.

00:38:31.610 --> 00:38:35.420
And it wasn't very good.

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:39.013
But they sort of always
believed in me, you know?

00:38:39.013 --> 00:38:40.430
And believed that
it was possible,

00:38:40.430 --> 00:38:41.810
when other people were,
like, oh, your kid's

00:38:41.810 --> 00:38:42.727
going to be in a band.

00:38:42.727 --> 00:38:45.932
And when I was not
gearing up for college,

00:38:45.932 --> 00:38:47.390
I think there was
a lot of judgment

00:38:47.390 --> 00:38:48.432
there from other parents.

00:38:48.432 --> 00:38:51.560
And they just said this is his
passion, and they backed it.

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:55.220
You know, I just would
say with anything, music

00:38:55.220 --> 00:38:59.690
or otherwise, if your kid's
got a passion for something--

00:38:59.690 --> 00:39:02.390
you know, I learned a lot
from my parents in that sense.

00:39:02.390 --> 00:39:06.020
They backed me 100%.

00:39:06.020 --> 00:39:08.070
And let him learn songs
he wants to learn.

00:39:08.070 --> 00:39:09.070
That's what I would say.

00:39:09.070 --> 00:39:11.060
It's important
that they can make

00:39:11.060 --> 00:39:13.280
the connection of why
they're learning music

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:14.750
to why they love music.

00:39:14.750 --> 00:39:20.120
and sometimes classical
is a great teaching tool.

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:22.970
But I'd say what I did was
every classical song I learned,

00:39:22.970 --> 00:39:24.520
I learned a Billy Joel tune.

00:39:24.520 --> 00:39:26.840
And I made my teacher do that.

00:39:26.840 --> 00:39:28.720
And she was this
scary, scary woman,

00:39:28.720 --> 00:39:31.703
and somehow she
still let me do it.

00:39:31.703 --> 00:39:32.203
Yeah.

00:39:32.203 --> 00:39:33.036
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:39:33.036 --> 00:39:34.040
ANDREW MCMAHON: Cheers.

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:36.290
SPEAKER: Thanks so much
for everyone for coming.

00:39:36.290 --> 00:39:38.095
Go buy his album,
"Upside Down Flowers"

00:39:38.095 --> 00:39:39.470
or listen to it
on YouTube music,

00:39:39.470 --> 00:39:41.053
or your favorite
subscription service.

00:39:41.053 --> 00:39:41.987
And thanks again.

00:39:41.987 --> 00:39:43.070
ANDREW MCMAHON: Thank you.

00:39:43.070 --> 00:39:43.778
I appreciate you.

00:39:43.778 --> 00:39:46.420
[APPLAUSE]

